summary: Pokemon Card of the Day #1516: Excadrill (Emerging Powers #56)
title: Pokemon Card of the Day #1516: Excadrill (Emerging Powers #56)
body:
Excadrill was an interesting study into the game in the BW era. It was a Pokemon that could dish out a reasonable amount of damage while the effect let you discard an Energy on the Defending Pokemon at the same time. This had to work, right? And yet, you never saw it. Could the competition really be high enough that even Drill Run wasn’t enough?

110 HP was pretty good on a Stage 1, though it was notable that Donphan existed with even higher bulk and a way to lessen damage. The Water Weakness could be a pain if something like Vanilluxe, Kyurem, Empoleon, or Keldeo EX showed up. At least there was a Lightning Resistance for the various partners to Eelektrik to work with, though that was nothing new for a Fighting-type. Needing 2 Energy to retreat meant that some help was nice, but you could pay for it once if you really had to.

Metal Claw only did 30 damage. Sure, it was for a single Colorless Energy, but 30 barely left a dent in anything that wasn’t a Pichu or Cleffa.

Drill Run was pretty good. 80 damage for 3 Fighting Energy wasn’t spectacular by any means but was very workable. Being able to discard an Energy on the Defending Pokemon made it a nice attack indeed! You’d think that would get Excadrill more consideration, but there were better things.

Excadrill was actually functional enough to use, but when you looked at it, you had to consider everything else. Donphan was a bulkier and slightly stronger Fighting-type that also had synergy with Zekrom, Kyurem, and Reshiram thanks to Earthquake. Terrakion was also stronger and bulkier while being a Basic Pokemon! That small damage boost to the other two was also very relevant since those could KO Mewtwo EX in 2 hits and Darkrai EX in 1. This left Excadrill, which was otherwise solid, with no place in a serious game.
